sec.p:
When a continuous signal is considered as the product h(t) = f (t)g(t) of a periodic signal f (t) with a known period T, and a trend g(t) that has little variation over a cycle, the classical method to uncouple them involves using moving averages (see, e.g. Hyndman (2021)):
g∗(t)=1T∫t−T/2t+T/2h(t′)dt′ \begin{document}$$\displaystyle g^{*}(t)=\frac{1}{T} \int_{t-T / 2}^{t+T / 2} h\left(t^{\prime}\right) d t^{\prime}$$\end{document}
(S1)
f∗(t)=h(t)/g∗(t) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} f^{*}(t)=h(t) / g^{*}(t) \tag{S1} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
where g∗(t) and f ∗(t) are the estimates of the trend and the periodic signal. When the assump-tions mentioned are met, the estimates coincide with the original functions.

In our case, however, many things are different. The most important are that we do not know what is the period of the “periodic” signal (in fact, we want an estimate of T if the signal is periodic at all), and that the signal is not continuous. The first feature implies that we ignore what is the “correct” value for the size for the moving average. The second feature forces us to convert the moving average integral into a sum with few terms. As a consequence, for a time series of the form f (0), f (4), f (8), …, representing observations on the number of eggs taken every 4 hours, we use the following equations for estimating the trend and the underlying periodic signal:
g∗(ti)=12n+1∑j=i−ni+nh(tj)f∗(ti)=h(ti)/g∗(ti) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{align*} & g^{*}\left(t_{i}\right)=\frac{1}{2 n+1} \sum_{j=i-n}^{i+n} h\left(t_{j}\right) \\ & f^{*}\left(t_{i}\right)=h\left(t_{i}\right) / g^{*}\left(t_{i}\right) \tag{S2} \end{align*}$$\end{document}
where ti is the time at which the i-th observation was made. We have used n = 3, corresponding to a moving average of roughly 28 hours (using n = 2, i.e. 20 hours, gives very similar results).

In order to test our method we apply it here to “synthetic” egg records, generated with the following model. We assume that there is an underlying signal f (t) of period T (time is measured in hours), given by
(S3)
f(t)=A(1+sin⁡(0.1+2πt/T), \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} f(t)=A(1+\sin (0.1+2 \pi t / T), \tag{S3} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
with A = 20 (maximum of eggs at each time point), and that this is corrupted by some additive noise n(t). For simplicity, n(t) is simply a random number uniformly chosen between 0 and A. The resulting signal is modulated by a decay given by g(t) = exp(−t/50). The total signal is then
(S4)
h(t)=int[g(t)(αf(t)+(1−α)n(t))],t∈{0,4,8,…,120}. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} h(t)=\operatorname{int}[g(t)(\alpha f(t)+(1-\alpha) n(t))], t \in\{0,4,8, \ldots, 120\} . \tag{S4} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
